    "Unknown": "Using hospitality (philoxenoi). \"Friendly to strangers,\" old word (from philos, xenos), in N.T. only here and 1Ti 3:2; Tit 1:",
    "Commentary Vol. 345": "Mr. Taylor elsewhere speaks thus: It may be alledged, that the Lord laid on him the Iniquities of us all, Isaiah `[char_Isaiah_Gen_26]` 53:",
    "A New and Concise Bible Dictionary": "Various symbolical references are made to the heifer. Samson called his wife a heifer with which others had ploughed to discover his riddle. Judges 14:\n9. The `[group_Canaanites_Gen_10]` washing of the feet of those that are clean, as taught by the Lord in John `[char_John_Ref]` 13 has this character of cleansing with water. The `[group_Canaanites_Gen_10]` Holy Spirit applies, by the word, the truth of the condemnation of sin in the cross of Christ to the heart and conscience, to purify the believer, without applying the blood again. Num. 19: 1-22; Heb. 9:",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "Then went Esau `[char_Esau_Gen_25]` unto Ishmael, etc.] Not to Ishmael in person, for [v_Gen_25_17] he was now dead, (<012517>Genesis 25:17), and had been dead as is reckoned about fourteen years before this, but to the house of Ishmael: and took unto the wives which he had; the daughters of Heth, and who seem by this to be both alive at this time: Mahalath the daughter of Ishmael, Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`\u2019s son; the same with [v_Gen_36_3] Bashemath, (<013603>Genesis 36:3); as the Targum of Jonathan expresses it, this person having two names, and is further described, the sister of Nebajoth, to be his wife; who was the eldest son of Ishmael, and, his father being dead, was the principal in the family; and this woman Esau took to wife was his sister by his mother\u2019s side, as the above Targum expresses, as well as by his father\u2019s; whereas he might have other sisters only by his father\u2019s side, he having had more wives than one. This Esau seems to have done in order to curry favour with his father, who was displeased with his other wives, and therefore takes one of his father\u2019s 504 brother\u2019s daughters; but in this he acted an unwise part, on more accounts than one; partly as it was taking to wife the daughter of one that was cast out of his grandfather\u2019s house, and had been a persecutor of his father, and therefore not likely to be agreeable to him; and partly as being a daughter of the bondmaid\u2019s son: children born of her could not inherit the land promised to Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` and Isaac.\nVer.\n9. It ripened into perfection by use, obedience and work. forty years later when he gave up Isaac and had God alone (James 2:22-23). QUESTIONS\n9. In what ways may the mind see an image invisible to others? Give an instance of each case.\n9. How did Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` receive the first and what were the steps of Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`'s faith?",
    "Warren W. Wiersbe": "means \u201cto shepherd\u201d (see Ps. 23), and \u201clift up\u201d means \u201cto carry like a child.\u201d Of course, the faithful shepherd sometimes has to carry the lambs, so the two images merge (Isa. 40:11). Though he was Israel\u2019s king, David `[char_David_Rut_4]` always saw himself as a shepherd (2 Sam. 24:17). Indeed, the nation of Israel is God\u2019s inheritance, for He has invested in them the spiritual treasures that the bankrupt world needs (Rom. 9:1\u20135). \u201cSalvation is of the Jews\u201d (John `[char_John_Ref]` 4:22). God has not forsaken His people."
